{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.05,0.14,0.38,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74013"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10985"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59489"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7431"},{"type":"tags","id":"7437"},{"type":"tags","id":"7438"},{"type":"tags","id":"7439"},{"type":"tags","id":"7441"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74013"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after twisting her knee while playing netball. She reports hearing a \u0027pop\u0027 at the time of injury and is now unable to bear weight on the affected leg. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. The right knee is swollen with a moderate effusion. There is tenderness over the anterior aspect of the knee, and the Lachman test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn MRI of the knee is performed, revealing a tear of the anterior cruciate ligament.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely involved in this injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial meniscus","Lateral meniscus","Medial collateral ligament","Anterior intercondylar area of the tibia","Posterior cruciate ligament"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic history and examination findings suggestive of an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) injury. The \u0027pop\u0027 sound, inability to bear weight, and positive Lachman test are indicative of an ACL tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior intercondylar area of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E is the site where the ACL attaches. Injury to the ACL often involves this area, leading to knee instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial meniscus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral meniscus\u003C/strong\u003E are cartilaginous structures that can also be injured in knee trauma, but they are not directly involved in ACL tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E is another stabilising ligament in the knee, but it is not typically involved in the mechanism of injury described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E provides stability to the inner side of the knee and is not directly related to the ACL or its attachment site.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior intercondylar area of the tibia is an important anatomical landmark for the attachment of the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL).","Injury to the ACL often involves the anterior intercondylar area, leading to instability of the knee joint.","Understanding the anatomy of the knee is crucial for diagnosing and managing knee injuries."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59489"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59489"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T09:02:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T10:22:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10985"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74013"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ